{"/service/ndnp/iune/batch_iune_heron_ver01/data/sn92053739/00542864813/1921033101/0144.xml":{"full_text":"Rpi\nn Baily Journal\nSt. Louis Daily Journal Co. Publishers\nTHE ONLY DAILY IN THE CITY\n\nEstablished in 1889\nI\ntered\nas second-class matter at the postoffice at Beat\nIllinois, under act of March 3, 187%.\niblished Every Week-Day Evening Except Saturday. Also\nSunday Morning.\nCopy.\nCopy,\nSUBSCRIPTION RATES:\ncents\nceats\n1\nI\nBy Carrier\nin East St. Louis and Suburbs\nPer Week. 80 OSBM\nand Sunday\nBy Mall (In Advance)\nPostage Prepaid Anywhere in United Stated\nMonth\nfee Months\n1 Months.\neYear\nDally and Sunday\nn cente\n2.00\n.80\nForeign\nlea.B. David (Inc.)....\nKeator\ning Representatives.\nAXre Lee Bergen\n.in Madison Ave., New York\nHartford Bldg., Chicage\n..Times Bldg.. BL Louis\ni\ncribers, who fail to receive their paper regularly, will\nconfer a favor by reporting the same to this office.\nNO. 322 BROADWAY, EAST ST. LOUIS, ILL\nEast 451 and 452.\nTELEPHONES\n.Kinloch, 8L Clair 2109 and 2110\nFIXING THE PRICE OF MILK.\nt According to an announcement made on Sat\narday, the milk producers and the milk distrib\ngtors reached an agreement to raise the whole\npie price of milk five cents the hundred pounds.\nThe assumption is, of course, that the distrib\nptors, who are the wholesalers, consented to the\nincrease.\nj As the increase is but slightly, more than two\nher cent, it probably will not be apparent in the\nRetail price. The wholesale price for April will\nbe $2.28 per hundred pounds, while the whole\npale price was $3 in April of last year, a de\nTease of twenty-four per cent for this year.\nOME BUILDING AND BUILDING COSTS.\nIt is anomalous, but true, that the price of\nmoney is less as its value is greater. The value j\nof money is increasing as prices are diminish- i\ning, and money will -soon be easier to get and\nthe cost of it will be somewhat lower than at:\nresent. The principal fact is, however, that\nS 7am. .dt mt b A V* =e A\u2014\u2014P c\ne value of money is becoming greater, and\nis alone will be an incentive to the revival of\nsiness.\n\u25a0\u25a0Manufacturers and merchants are wisely tak-\u0964\ning their losses. They have been disposing of\ncommodities produced at high cost or bought at\n(high prices. They will be prepared to do busi\nness on the new basis of reduced costs and low\nter prices. Their losses have been very heavy,\n\u201ctoo.\nThe statement of President James F. Galvin\nRof the East St. Louis Real Estate Exchange,\nthat \u201cthe only way to get rents to come down.\nris to have houses go up,\u201d is particularly applica\nrble to this city. There was a shortage of houses\nF for several years prior to the beginning of the\ni war. Many thousands of persons, possibly as\nmany as 8,000, live in St. Louis and in Illinois\ntowns adjacent to East St. Louis because they\nhave been unable to buy, rent or lease desirable\nhouses or apartments in this city, where they\nwould prefer to live.\nThe number of inhabitants of East St. Louis\nis 66,740, but the potential population is 80,000\nto 85,000. Unless homes and apartment houses i\nare built, our population may stand still, though1\nour industrial development may be remarkable.\nAs Mr. Galvin also said in his interview in\nSunday\u2019s Journal, the stocks of construction\nmaterials and supplies have diminished, which\nindicates that supply and material companies j\nhave disposed of high-priced stocks. Materials\nare one of the two principal items of cost. The j\nother important item is labor. The cost of la- i\nbor has not come down, nor has the cost of\nmany raw materials declined enough, and work- j\nmen engaged in the building industry in most\nplaces have taken a determined stand against j\nwage decreases. Needless to say, lack of de-1\nmand will persist until the large cost-items of)\nmaterial and labor are largely decreased.\nIf the building of homes and apartments,)\neven- of factories, is retarded, it will pot be on i\naccount of the value or cost of money, but of\nthe high total cost of construction. As soon as\ni the total cost of construction descends to a de\ncidedly low level, building operations will go'\nforward on a record scale. But the total cost!\nlevel will have to be very low, because, as Mr. i\nGalvin says, there is a strong, inherent de-i\nmand which will have the effect of tending to'\nraise prices and costs quickly. The level will\nhave to be low enough to permit of increases to\nnormal, high levels, so that an abnormally high!\nlevel will not be attained too quickly and result\nin a series of reactionary conditions.\nMAKING LIFE MORE LIVABLE.\n3 The assertion that we Americans are motor\nmad, that we are sorely afflicted with \u201cacute;\nmotoritis,\" may be a clever one, but aside from I\nmere cleverness in phrasing it does not add I\nanything to the discussion. It may be held that I\njust as we were once \u201cbike crazy\u201d so we have I\nI\nnow gone wild over the automobile; but thisj\nwould not be true.\nAt the close of last year there were register\nF\nj ed in this country 9,211,295 motor vehicles; but\nit is futile to conclude from this, as is being;\ndone in some quarters, that like the bicycle the j\nmotor car is presently to go into the discard.)\nWhile it is true that the riding 6f bicycles as it\nwas once practiced is no longer being indulged!\nin. it is also true that the number of bicycles!\nin existence today is hardly less than it was a\nyear ago, or ten years ago.\nL in a greatmeasure the bicycle was given up\nsby people who took to the motor car as a more\npeople who took to the motor car as a more\neffective means of getting about; at least those\nthat could afford it did so.\nAnd just as they\nused the two-wheeled vehicle to expedite the\nbusiness of the day, so these persons are this\nday using the motor car for many things be\nsides pleasure rides. For many people the own\nership of an automobile merely means that they\ncan carry on with more dispatch the business\nof the day.\nIf it is analyzed correctly what this increase\nin motor cars means is that we have raised fair\nly generally our. standard of living. No doubt\nthe phenomenon would surprise anyone who had\nleft the civilized world forty years ago and came\nback to it today. But he would be surprised at\nmore than the number of motor vehicles now\nto be seen on the streets. He would be sur\nprised at the number of so-called luxuries which\nhave become necessities among us. And'all of\nthese so-called luxuries have made life more\nlivable; they have extended our reach and\nraised life from the plane of the primitive.\nThe development of the automobile and its\nincreasing use is only one more indication that\nour standard of living has been raised.\nWe\nknow what we want and, even at the cost of\nsome little hardship, if that is necessary, we\nare going to get it We may call it \"motoritis\"\nif we like, but the point is that it is a good thing\nto have, and that it will endure until something\neven- better than the motor car makes its ap\npearance.\nAnd then we shall go in for that.\nA RECKLESS FRENCHMAN.\nThe statement of a French senator that the\nUnited States has never repaid a loan obtained\nfrom the king of France in 1778 was ill advised;\nfor the preponderance of evidence is against\nthe truth of the assertion, and the incident will\nbe seized upon and exploited by those desirous\nof fomenting bad feeling between the two na\ntions. Already expressions of indignation are\narising from Americans \"who rashly assume\nthat the senator speaks for France, and that\nFrance is seeking a pretext to evade payment of\nher war debt to the United States.\nIt is reassuring to learn that some French\nmen realize the unwisdom of discussing the sub\nject in the spirit shown by the senator. One of\nhis colleagues, for example, replied to him as\nfollows: \u201cI must ask pardon, but it would be\ndangerous for the good relations which it is in\ndispensable to maintain with the United States\nto open such a discussion if really this debt has\nbeen paid.\u201d\nThere are in this country persons who would\nbe delighted to have a strain placed on the\nfriendship between the United States and\nFrance. Some of them deliberately and openly\ntried to foster ill feeling against our ally not\nlong-since by holding a meeting in New York at\nwhich French soldiers were accused of atrocities\nagainst Germans. French politicians are short\nsighted indeed if they, unwittingly or not, abet\nthese propagandists by expressing sentiments\nthat are apt to cause irritation in the United\nStates.\nThe life that would be full of meaning can\nalso be full of meanness.\nThe Quebec neighbors of the Stillmans do\nnot deny that they were curious.\nThe man who falls for everything usually ac\ncumulates a lot of financial bruises.\nThe number of fields already plowed does not\nindicate that the farmers intend to strike this\nspring.\nSome of the biggest things in history have\nbeen accomplished with no backing except\nbrains.\nAmong Our Contemporaries\nNOW ON THE UPGRADE.\n(Danville Commercial-News.)\nThe business depression has been weathered and the\ncountry is now on the upward trend. All barometers\nof business join in emphasizing the rapid recovery of\nthe country from the stagnation of the winter and fall.\nThe new business era will be quite different from the\n\u201csilk shirt\u201d financial period, but it will bring a fair\nprofit to the business man and an honest wage for an\nhonest day of toil to the laboring man.\n\u201cThe bottom of the business depression has been\nreached and passed,\u201d says Henry Ford.\nMr.-Ford, it will be remembered, was among'the\nvery first to begin cutting prices. He saw into the\nfuture. Prices were at the peak, when he announced a\ncut and within a very short time, cuts were announced\nby practically all motor car corporations as well as\nother lines of business.\nThe automobile factories, first hit by the financial\ndepression, are the first to respond to the revival in in\ndustry and are opening up their plants.\nIp Danville one department of the Allith-Prouty\ncompany has been reopened after remaining idle for\nseveral months. It is merely an indication close at hand\nof the revival in business and renewal of operations on\na large scale.\nOf course Europe continues a madhouse of wrang\nling factions and in our own country grave problems\nmust be settled, dealing with the railroads and the\nhousing situation, but there is work to do and it can\nnot wait.\nSince 1914 little has been done throughout the en\ntire world except to bend our energies to satisfy the\nlust of the war god. The world is seven years behind\nand must catch up. Industrial stagnation could not\nlast. There is too much to do in the world.\nThe eyes of the administration at Washington are\nturned toward America. The administration realizes,]\nof course, that the prosperity and happiness of the citi\nzens of this country are bound up with the destiny of\nthe old world. Europe must be helped but for the next\nfour years, America and not Europe will come first.\nThe American business man should look forward\nwith high courage to the opportunities offered for serv\nice and profit. Within a very short time it is, going to\nbe full speed ahead.\n1\nBy Heroic and Strenuous Work Mr, Fan Secures the Precious Tickets\nI 607 /N CANE 77\u2018\nBASE MIL T/CKETSALE\nAN\u2019 BOUGHT T^iO FOR\n7HQPBMN6 GF MB!\nOH JOHV\nMY H^RO!\nBhrebh,\nMMELVIEWS\"9NEWS\nIn MGozOarsaaneEcaRAS*\n\u201cFROZEN NORTH LARGELY A MYTH\u201d\u2014STEFANNSON.\nI\n\u2018T\nHE frozen North is largely a myth,\u201d declares Vilhjalmur Stef\nannson, noted explorer. He points out that he has found fertile\nvalleys with all sorts of life far above the arctic circle. The\narctic region forms a coming empire which will supply the world with\nmost of its meat within fifty years, he says.\n\u201cThe American school geography,\" he continues, \"is the most\nwidely read bit of fiction in the United States. It informs you that\nthere is practically no life north of the arctic circle, that there is noth\ning but a barren waste of snow and ice.\n\u201cThe arctic explorer himself also is largely responsible for foster\ning this myth. It is so often not only pleasant but exceedingly profit\nable to pose as a hero. If, when I come back from the North, you think\nI have been coping with wondrous hardships you will worship me as a\nhero. And if I annear a little reticent you will love me for my modesty.\nI\nAll I have to do is not to give the game away. And\nthen there is the missionary. The missionaries in\nthe north are doing a very excellent work\u2014at least,\nthey say it is\u2014but it costs money. If when they\ncome back they find the popular impression has got\nabroad that they have been enduring untold hard\nships from cold and hunger they find it helpful in\nloosening the purse strings.\n\u2018Yes,\u2019 they say, \u2018It was pretty cold at times and\nit did get pretty lonesome.\u2019 And they are applauded\nfor their modesty.\n\"The coldest temperature at the north pole is 60\ndegrees below zero. The coldest ever reported in the\nUnited States was 68 degrees below zero at Havre,\nMont. The United States weather bureau maintains\na station on the north coast of Alaska. It frequently\nreports a summer temperature of 100 in the shade.\nI\n1\nI\nI\nI\nI\nAna me COICESL Lemptraturt uUrE, &UU LtCs MUltu\nof the arctic circle, is 54 degrees below zero.\nV. Stefannson.\n\u201cWhen I was a boy in North Dakota I frequently walked five miles\nto school in weather 50 degrees below zero. I didn\u2019t especially con\nsider myself a hero then.\u201d\nThe history of the world, Mr. Stefannson said, had been the history\nof the conquest of the \u201cfrozen north.\u201d\n\u201cI suppose if Memphis, Egypt, had an advertising club like yours\n3,000 years ago, the returned traveler, lecturing before it, would say\nthat all north of the Mediterranean was a frozen, sterile waste where\nnothing would grow,\" he said.\n\u201cIn the days of the Roman empire the \u2018frozen north\u2019 was all north\nof the Alps. Today we have the same old myth, considering the\n'frozen north\u2019 all above the arctic circle.\u201d\nStefannson says 250 specimens of vegetation had been found on\nBanks island, 400 miles north of the arctic circle, and 750 specimens\nhad been counted on the north coast of Alaska.\nI\nDo You Remember?\nT\nYour Dad Read These Happenings In The Daily Journal in 1896\n(Reprinted from old files of The Daily Journal, March 31, 1921.)\nMr. and Mrs. S. H. Horn of 318\nCollinsville avenue entertained\na\nnumber of young folks at their home\nlast evening in honor of the six\nteenth anniversary of the birth of\ntheir son Steve.\nThe evening was\nspent in games and music, also danc\ning.\nDelicious refreshments were\nserved to the following: Misses\nPearl Bobel, Mattie Johnson, Mabel\nJames, Mattie Horn, Rose Case,\nGrace Campbell, Nellie Horn, Frank\nCollier, Oscar Bobel, S. Cash,' Ed\nJalageas, Arthur Cockrel, William\nBauchens\nMrs. James Sullivan of 1106 Cleve\nland avenue entertained the mem\nbers of the Jean Ingelow Club, at\nher home yesterday.\nPrizes were]\nawarded to Mesdames F. B. Jordan,\nC. Hartman and G. Suprunowski.\nI\nMrs. J. C. Lange celebrated the\nanniversary of her birth with a par\nty at her home, 106 Collinsville av\nenue last evening.\nThe work of felling a large cotton\nwood tree on the premises of Dr.\nFekete in the three hundred block on\nCollinsville this morning caused a\nlarge crowd to congregate. The chop\npers knew their business and the\nlarge tree over four feet in diameter\nfell just where they wanted it to.\nThe Todd Stanley pulley manufac\nturing plant is- being removed from\nSt. Louis to East St. Louis today.\nA lodge of the Degree of Honor\nwill be organized in East St. Louis\nthis evening at a meeting to be held\nin Geary\u2019s hall.\nWHOSWHO\nIN THE\nPAY'S\nNEWS\nJUSTICE EDWARD DOUGLASS\nWHITE.\nEdward Douglass White, chief\njustice of the United States Supreme\ncourt, may retire soon because of\nill health, according to rumors from\nWashington. That he has been de\nsirous of resigning for some time is\ngenerally known.\nHis departure\nfrom\nme\nHU\npreme bench will\nbe a loss, as he\nis one of the\ncommanding fig\nires of the ju- 4\ndicial world.\nWhite is\nan\nold Confederate1\nsoldier and\na\nlife long Demo\ncrat from Lou\nisiana. The late\nSenator Randall\n-44\nE.D/HITE\nGibson or that\nstate, a devoted\nadherent of Grover Cleveland, urged\nthe president in 1894 to place Sena\ntor White, Gibson\u2019s colleague and\nkinsman*, on the supreme court\nbench. White was then one of the\nmost eminent lawyers in the coun\ntry and the president was glad to\nappoint him as an associate justice.\nMoreover, existing differences be\ntween President Cleveland and the\nsenate made the appointmnt espe\ncially desirable, as it smoothed the\nway for confirmation at a time when\nthere was reluctance to confirm any\nof his appointees.\nJustice White had been on the\nbench nearly seventeen years when\nPresident Taft, in December, 1910,\nnominated him for chief justice. The\nnomination came as a great surprise\nto the senate and to the country and\nmore especially to Justice Hughes,\nwhom Taft had appointed as an as\nsociate justice of the court in the\nprevious November.\nBefore appointing Justice White\nas the presiaing judge of the court,\nthe president had assured Justice\nHughes'\" friends, it was stated at the\ntime, that the New Yorker woukt\nThe\nbe advanced to this position,\nsenate then contained twenty-five'\nRepublican majority and Hughes\nTHE MASTER\u2019S GOLDIN RULE\u2014\nst med should de to you, r\nAs ye would that med_\ndo ye also to them\u2014Luke G. 31.\n7ou,\ncould have been advanced to the\nchief place without serious opposi\ntion, though the proposal to make\nhim chief justice was criticised by\nmany Republican senators on the\nground that both' in age and service\nas he was the youngest man on the\nbench and that to advance him over\na man like White would be a blow at\nthe dignity and standing of the\ncourt.\nOver night, it was alleged, the\npresident changed his mind and sent\nJustice Whtie\u2019s nomination for chief\njustice to the senate, as the succes\nsor of the late Chief Justice Fuller.\nThe nomination was promptly con\nfirmed.\ndalat\nDINNERSTORIES\n\u201cLet's go in here for luncheon.;\nYou don't have to tip the waiters.\u201d i\n\u201cHow do they manage it?\u201d\n\u201cEasy enough. You pay twice as\nmuch for your food.\u201d\ni\n\u201cMrs. Blueblood \u2018brags about her j\nancestors, but I don\u2019t believe they\namounted to much\u2014they couldn\u2019t!\neven afford to keep servants.\u201d\n\"How-do you know that?\u201d\n\"Mrs. Blueblood showed me a set\nof dishes that she said had been in\nthe family for more than a hundred\nyears.\u201d\n\"Was the wedding a success?\u201d\n\"Indeed it was. Why, women wept!\nbitterly who didn\u2019t even know the\nbride.\u201d\n\u201cDabbs is going to start a matri\nmonial agency.\u201d\n\u201cWhat got him going that way?\u201d\n\u201cSays he can see great possibili-,\nties in that business now that photo- i\ngraphs can be sent by wire.\u201d\nA baby will make love stronger,\nILLINOIS ROADS\nEQUIPMENT LIGHT\nState Could Not Fur\nnish Materials Fast\nEnough to Complete\nWork on Time.\nSpringfield, March 31.\u2014Road build\ning by convicts or state operated\nplants, is meeting with opposition in\nalmost every state in the country,\naccording to reports received by the\nBureau cf Roads of the Department\nThe non-feasibility\nof Agriculture.\nof the much agitated plan, it is claim\ned, recently was demonstrated in a\ncapacity survey of the state's equip\nment to build roads in Illinois.\nThe survey of the state\u2019s capacity\nwas made following a proposal that\nGov. Len Small use the convicts to\noperate state owned material plants.\nIt was found that the entire equip\nment of the state, which is as well\nequipped, if not better, than any\nother state in the country, could not\nturn out more than 15 car loads of\ncrushed stone daily. This quantity,\naccording to road engineers, is in\nfinitesimal.\nTo attempt such an undertaking\nand acquire equipment that would\ntake care of the state\u2019s needs, would\nex\nrequire the expenditure of a stu\npendous sum and long delay in start\ning the road building plan, it was\nstated. Illinois is already about two\nyears behind in its road building\nplan, it was stated, and according to\nstatistics of the Bureau of Agricul\nture, the state ranks twenty-sixth in\npoint of good highways.\nThe practicality of using the state\nconvicts to do the work is seriously\nquestioned by experts, and Gov.\nSmall is reported not in favor of as\nsuming the responsibility of inaug\nurating such a plan. Because of the\nagitation it was temporarily consid\nered, however.\nThose behind the movement are\nsaid to have overlooked the long de\nlay that must necessarily ensue while\nthe equipment was being acquired.\nAlso it is said that any further delay\nin the Illinois road building plan\nwould lose the people many millions\nof dollars because of the lack of\ngood highways.\nThe cost of bad roads thus far en\ndured \"would be perpetuated in\ndefinitely and unless prompt atten\ntion is given to this year\u2019s road build\ning program, Illinois will not catch\nup in a whole generation, the engi\nneers say.\nThe recent bond issue\nwas voted with the direction that al\nmost 4,000 miles of hard surface\nroads were to be built.\nDuring 1921 it was proposed to at\ntempt to catch up on the last two\nyears somewhat by constructing\nabout 500 miles. Recently it was de\ncided to begin the program by build\ning 123 miles, but the new bids have\nnot been called for except on 15\nmiles, and there is a probability that\nthe road season may slip away with\nnot eVen that amount completed.\nThe hope had been expressed in\nresolutions adopted by several motor\nist organizations and requests of\nbusiness concerns, that the road\nbuilding program be started imme\ndiately under the individual\ncom\npetitive contract plan. In the mean\ntime, while road building was being\ncarried on, the state could experi\nment and develop a system to do its\nown work and avoid the costliness of\ndelaying progress.\nVote the Citizens Non-Partisan\nTicket\u2014Adv.\n94\nThe days are getting longer, but\nthe months are just as short to the\nrenter.\ndays shorter, nights longer, bank\nroll smaller, home happier, clothes\nshabbier, the past forgotten and the\nfuture worth living for.\n\u201cDo tell us about the great wild\nwest,\" said the impressionable young\nwoman.\n\u201cYou may not believe it,\u201d replied\ntne tourist, \u201cbut I found a little town\nin North Dakota where there was\nnot a single moving picture theater.\u201d\n0\nN\u2018SPURR MOMENT\nTO A LADY, AGED TWELVE.\n(With a little pencil case.)\nDearie, this rift is poor I know,\nBut poor indeed am I.\nI\u2019d wish \u2019twere grander\u2014still somehow v\nMy trust is that you\u2019ll try\nTo take it whence it comes and then\nPerhaps you\u2019ll understand\nThat you shall have some real things when\nMy ships begin td land.\nIf hopes were cash and thoughts were all,\nYou\u2019d have a great big lot\nOf ev'rything for which you\u2019d call\u2014\nYet, dear, such things are not\nStill, if you'll search this little case,\nMaybe you\u2019ll find somewhere,\nDown in a tiny, secret place,\nMy heart is hiding there.\n\u2014George Taggart\n\nThe telephone says that a woman in a town on Long Island had can.\ncelled her contract with the telephone company on the grounds that al\nthough they had agreed to put her on a 'four-party line\u201d they had in fact\nput her on a line on which she was the ONLY subscriber.\nIf you happen to live in a town like the one mentioned, and you are\ntalking to a friend over a \"four-party line,\" be sure to speak in a language\nwhich nobody else can understand.\nVERY GOOD, ALEXANDER.\nDear Roy\u2014During a recent blizzard I happened to bserve several\nstreet cleaners huddled around a big can of burning trash perched on a\nsnow pile. Suddenly one of the men, who was without overcoat or gloves.,\nput his hand into the smoking flames and pulled out a little thing that\nonce bad been a doll\u2014dirty, broken and singed. The Italian (such he ap\npeared to be) regarded it lovingly for some time, and then looked over the\nhousetops with a smile. I imagined he was looking in the direction of his\nAfter carefully wiping the grimy plaything on a newspaper be\nhome.\nwrapped it up and put it in his pocket. Then he blew into his hands and\npicked up a snow shovel.\u2014Alexander.\n\nWe are indebted to.Rev. Harry Emerson Fosdick for a statement to\nthe effect that Mr. Methuselah of Genesis would never have lived his 969\nyears if he had tried to live them in New York. He would have wasted\naway his vitality and would not have lived more than 400 or 500 years,\nwhich is all on account of the nervous strain attached to life in that city.\nBut, actually. we believe the* old gentleman would have had more fun.\nThose 969 years must have been pretty dull for the old boy, with no\nmusical shows, no ball games, no prize lights, no six-day bicycle races, no\ndafces, no cabarets, no poker games. By the way, what did they do back\nin those ancient days to pass away the time? Anybody who would not\nrather live 400 years in New York than 969 back with old Methuselah must\nhave poor taste. And who could afford to live in New York even 400 years?\nNobody but the Standard Oil Company.\nNot that it makes any difference, but Emma May Dye lives in Martin's\nFerry, O. s.","height":"29772","width":"20800"}}
